Taking the Long View: A Look at Surveillance Before the Internet, Labor Before Capitalism, and a Technological Map of History
By Claudette Raynor 
---
Excerpt: This essay argues that the dominant frameworks for understanding the present — surveillance capitalism, labor decline, technological rupture — describe as new what is in fact ancient. Behavioral surveillance predates Google by millennia, the mid-twentieth-century pro-labor settlement is the historical anomaly rather than the baseline, and existing legal tools remain more adequate to the digital era than the discourse admits. The piece introduces three timeline documents that trace labor, surveillance, technology, and regulation across the longest arc the author could assemble and is published here as instruments for critical reflection and thinking about these subjects.
---
Current literature and media tells a story or (his)tory about surveillance capitalism in which Google's pivot toward behavioral data extraction in 2001 marks something categorically new — a fresh economic logic, threat, and injury to human autonomy. It also tells a story about labor in which the Wagner Act and the postwar industrial settlement represent the natural baseline from which the present represents a fall. It is also a story about technology in which each new wave — radio, television, the internet, artificial intelligence — arrives as a rupture, demanding regulatory frameworks that did not exist before it.

These his(stories) are not exactly wrong. They are, more interestingly, incomplete in ways that obscure much of what is actually happening.

My current work, has been trying to make these histories more complete or visible. More recently, I worked on building a set of timelines that attempt to render this history more legible to anyone who is interested or curious about it. They are working documents, not pronouncements, and meant to be used as instruments for thinking rather than conclusions to be received.

The conversation that produced this

Over the course of an unusually generative thinking session, working with an AI as a thinking partner rather than an author, I traced a series of arguments that began with Hal Varian's economic theory of behavioral data and ended somewhere I had not expected: at the recognition that virtually every major framework we use to describe the present moment treats as new what is in fact ancient. Shoshana Zuboff, whose Age of Surveillance Capitalism (2019) has become the canonical popular text on matters of capitalism, technology, and surveillance that locates the origin of behavioral data extraction in Google's commercial development of search advertising between 2001 and 2004. It is empirically correct that something distinctive happens in that period, but Zuboff is analytically incomplete about what it is.

Audience measurement at industrial scale began in 1923, when Archibald Crossley started selling ratings of radio listeners to advertisers. The advertising-supported broadcast model itself began in 1922, with AT&T's WEAF in New York airing the first paid radio advertisement. The credit reporting industry — building detailed behavioral files on individuals to sell predictions about them to commercial entities — was operating at scale by the 1860s. The Domesday Book, William the Conqueror's comprehensive 1086 survey of essentially every economic resource in England, was a population-level surveillance project of a kind that the most ambitious surveillance state of the twenty-first century has not exceeded in its ambition, only in its technical means. The Roman census predates the birth of Christ. The Code of Hammurabi, around 1754 BCE, includes wage controls and labor regulations that any modern labor lawyer would recognize.

What Zuboff identifies as a new economic system is better understood as a new commodity domain within a very old economic logic. The laws of motion that Ellen Meiksins Wood traced in her work on the origins of capitalism — the competitive compulsion to reinvest surplus in productivity-enhancing innovation, the structural requirement that producers be market-dependent for their own reproduction — are the same laws of motion that govern the platform era. What has changed is not the system but the substance of what is being commodified. The human, rendered in digital form, has been brought inside the commodity frame in a way that previous capitalism could not technically achieve. Marx's concept of the commodity fetish — the misrecognition of social relations as object-properties — completes a recursive loop that Marx anticipated structurally but could not have specified concretely. We are not just buying and selling commodities anymore. We are, in some real sense, the commodities being bought and sold, while continuing to experience ourselves as the subjects doing the buying.

This is not a refutation of Zuboff. It is, I think, a sharpening of her argument that her own framework prevents her from making. She locates the harm correctly. She mislocates the novelty. And in doing so, she inadvertently makes the political response harder than it needs to be, because she frames the problem as requiring new analytical and legal tools when in fact the classical tools — antitrust, constitutional privacy doctrine, common-carrier regulation, consumer protection — remain adequate to the task. They simply require the political will to be applied to the domain they were never explicitly designed for but that they can absolutely reach.

What the charts reveal

The timelines I have built are an attempt to make this long arc visible to anyone who wants to see it. There are several integrated documents, each building on the last, and they trace the same threads — labor, communications, surveillance, monopoly and concentrated economic power, and the regulatory responses to each — across the longest time horizon I could honestly assemble.

A pre-timeline covers antiquity through 1791, with particular density through the medieval and early modern periods, where the institutional DNA of modern labor regulation actually gets laid down. The Statute of Labourers of 1351 — passed after the Black Death created labor scarcity that workers tried to leverage into higher wages, freezing wages at pre-plague levels and criminalizing both demanding and offering higher pay — established a principle of state intervention in labor markets favoring employers that has never really been retired. The pattern recurs through Tudor wage statutes, through the English Combination Acts of 1799-1800, through In re Debs in 1895, through Taft-Hartley in 1947, through PATCO in 1981, through contemporary right-to-work laws. The state has been siding with employers against labor in conditions of worker scarcity for at least 3,500 years. The mid-twentieth-century period when state power partially aligned with workers — the Wagner Act, the New Deal industrial settlement, the postwar welfare states — is the historical anomaly that requires explanation, not the post-1980 decline that is consistent with the long pattern.

The main timeline covers 1791 through the present, tracing every major technical innovation alongside the regulatory response it produced — and, crucially, the lag between them. The telephone (1876) does not produce comprehensive federal regulation until the Kingsbury Commitment of 1913. The Audion vacuum tube (1906) does not produce broadcasting regulation until the Radio Act of 1927. The HTTP cookie (1994) has, thirty-two years later, still not produced comprehensive U.S. federal regulation. The lag from innovation to regulation runs from a few months — the Titanic sinking in April 1912 produced the Radio Act of August 1912, the fastest invention-to-regulation chain in the timeline — to many decades or never. Reading these patterns side by side reveals that the question "is the technology too new for existing law" is consistently the wrong question. The right question is whether there is political will to apply the law that exists. And the answer has historically depended on whether a documented abuse becomes politically intolerable, not on whether the legal framework is conceptually adequate.

A third version expands the timeline globally, interweaving the labor and regulatory histories of Britain (Combination Acts, Tolpuddle Martyrs, Chartism, the General Strike, the Miners' Strike), France (the Loi Le Chapelier, the Paris Commune, May 1968, the Yellow Vests, the pension protests), Germany (Bismarck's social insurance, the SPD, Weimar labor law, the destruction of independent unions under Nazism, the postwar settlement), Russia and the Soviet Union (the 1861 emancipation of serfs, the 1905 and 1917 revolutions, the Gulag, the postwar communist labor framework, Solidarity, the post-1991 shock therapy), China (the Republican-era factory regulations, the 1949 revolution, the Cultural Revolution, the 1978 Reform and Opening Up, the 1994 Labor Law, the contemporary state-managed labor market), India (the colonial Factory Acts, the 1926 Trade Unions Act, post-independence labor framework, the Bhopal disaster), and many other national histories. The U.S. exceptionalism on labor and data protection — the fact that the U.S. has consistently lagged Europe on factory regulation, on social insurance, on data protection, and now on AI regulation — emerges clearly only when placed against the comparative international story.

Each entry in these timelines carries a bidirectional pointer: forward to the regulation or consequence the event eventually triggered, and backward, on each regulatory entry, to the inventions, abuses, or labor events that produced it. A reader can trace any chain forward or backward through time. The Audion vacuum tube becomes the start of a thread that runs through KDKA Pittsburgh's first commercial broadcast in 1920, through the spectrum chaos of the 1920s, through the Radio Act of 1927, through the Communications Act of 1934, through the FCC's cable rules of 1965, through the Telecommunications Act of 1996, through the current contests over net neutrality. Tom Carter's invention of the Carterfone in 1965 becomes the start of a thread that runs through the FCC's 1968 decision permitting customer-owned equipment on AT&T's network, through MCI's authorization the same year, through the AT&T breakup of 1984, through the entire architecture of the consumer internet that follows.

The charts do not argue. They show. The interpretation belongs to the reader.

What the long view changes about the present

A few patterns become visible from the long view that the short-horizon framings cannot see.

The first is that surveillance of populations is not a digital phenomenon but a state phenomenon. From Mesopotamian tax records around 3000 BCE through the Roman census, through the Domesday Book, through Louis XIV's cabinet noir mail surveillance of 1665, through the first U.S. Census of 1790, through the credit bureaus of the 1860s, through the audience measurement industry of the 1920s, through Cold War signals intelligence, through PRISM, the principle that the state systematically knows its subjects in order to extract resources from them and shape their behavior is continuous with the dawn of recorded history. The modern surveillance state is an intensification of an ancient pattern, not a categorically new phenomenon. What is genuinely new in the digital era is the integration of commercial behavioral inference with state surveillance, the speed and granularity of the feedback loops, and the recursive property that the surveilled population is now also the producer of the surveillance product. These are real novelties. But they are intensifications within a pattern, not departures from it.

The second is that the regulatory toolkit we have inherited is more adequate to the present than the cultural conversation around it suggests. The Sherman Antitrust Act of 1890 has been used against Standard Oil, against AT&T, against IBM, against Microsoft, against Motorola and Google's standard-essential patents, and is being used now against Google's search business and Meta's social networking monopoly. The Fourth Amendment, written in 1791, has been extended through Katz v. United States in 1968 to cover telephone conversations and through Carpenter v. United States in 2018 to cover cell-site location information. The Federal Trade Commission Act of 1914 provides the authority for every contemporary FTC privacy enforcement action. The Fair Information Practice Principles articulated in a 1973 U.S. government report are the conceptual backbone of GDPR. The European Convention on Human Rights of 1950 is what underlies the European court decisions establishing the right to be forgotten and limiting U.S.-EU data transfers. The legal infrastructure exists. What is missing is acknowledgment that the digital extension of the person is part of the person — and therefore that the protections we have built for the embodied person extend to the data shadow, the behavioral profile, the algorithmic identity that travels through commercial and governmental systems shaping the embodied person's life.

The third is that labor's relationship to technology has never been Luddite in the dismissive sense in which the term has been weaponized. The original Luddites, the skilled English textile workers who destroyed power looms between 1811 and 1816, were defending their economic position against employers' use of technology to break their bargaining power. They were not anti-technology. They were anti-displacement, anti-exploitation, and largely correct about what the new technology would do to skilled craft labor in their lifetimes. The pattern recurs continuously. The Knights of Labor in the 1880s. The IWW in the 1910s. The CIO industrial unions of the 1930s confronting Taylorist scientific management. The 1970s confrontation with offshoring. The 2010s gig economy classification disputes. The 2023 WGA and SAG-AFTRA strikes centering AI displacement as a contract issue. Worker concerns about technological displacement have been consistently dismissed and consistently vindicated by the historical record. The pattern is so consistent that one wonders why we keep being surprised by it.

The fourth, and perhaps the most useful, is that we are not in fact watching a fall. We are watching a transition. The framings that dominate popular discourse — surveillance capitalism, the end of work, the death of democracy, the dissolution of the family, the loneliness epidemic, the AI takeover — are mostly variations on a declinist theme that takes the mid-twentieth-century arrangement as a baseline and reads the present as departure. But the mid-twentieth-century arrangement was itself a brief and historically unusual configuration produced by very specific conditions: postwar reconstruction, Cold War welfare-state competition, the temporary alignment of capital and labor in the industrial-democratic consensus, the institutional residue of older religious and civic structures still providing belonging as a byproduct of arrangements that were dissolving for other reasons. The dissolution is real. So are the gains that come with it — the unprecedented expansion of individual self-authorship, the liberation from economic survival contracts that previous generations had to organize their lives around, the access to knowledge and community that no prior civilization made available at this scale. The question is not whether to mourn the dissolution or celebrate the gains. The question is what direction the transition is heading, and how we steer.

The timelines are navigational instruments for that question. They do not answer it. They make it answerable.

A note on method, and an invitation

This work was built with AI assistance, used as a thinking partner and research accelerator rather than an author. The framework, the integrations, the analytical claims, the structural choices about what to include and what to flag as uncertain — those are mine. What the AI provided was rapid surfacing of historical and academic context that would otherwise have required weeks of library work for each entry, plus the friction of having to articulate my own positions clearly enough that the tool could usefully reflect them back. This is, I think, one of the genuine emerging possibilities of the current moment — not the replacement of the writer but the acceleration of integrative thinking for writers who know what they are trying to do. Used otherwise, AI produces the slop that critics correctly fear. The difference is human direction.

The timelines are made available here as working documents, not finished scholarship. They contain analytical interpretations marked as such. They contain dates and attributions that should be verified against primary sources before serious citation. They contain gaps where coverage is uneven, particularly outside the Western contexts that my own training and reading have privileged. They are offered in the spirit of useful scaffolding for anyone interested in thinking longer and more carefully about how we got to where we are, and about the much longer arcs inside which the present moment sits.

For readers who want to follow these threads further, the works I have drawn on most directly include Ellen Meiksins Wood's The Origin of Capitalism: A Longer View (2002) for the laws-of-motion framework; Shoshana Zuboff's The Age of Surveillance Capitalism (2019) for the empirical case studies even where the larger framework requires sharpening; Lawrence Lessig's Code and Other Laws of Cyberspace (1999, updated 2006) for the foundational argument about architectural regulation; Frank Pasquale's The Black Box Society (2015) for algorithmic accountability; E.P. Thompson's The Making of the English Working Class (1963) for the classical labor-history scaffolding; Claudia Goldin's Career and Family (2021) for the demographic and labor-market history of women's economic emergence; Robert Putnam's Bowling Alone (2000) and The Upswing (2020) for the social-capital story; Byung-Chul Han's various works for the most rigorous contemporary philosophical diagnosis of what digital capitalism does to subjectivity; and the long bibliography of standard reference works that any timeline project necessarily draws on. The pre-modern entries draw on the Cambridge Ancient History, Cambridge Medieval History, and the standard surveys of medieval economic and labor history including Steven Epstein's work on guilds and S.R. Epstein on the medieval economy.

The timelines themselves are linked below. They are freely available, freely usable, and welcome correction. They are working drafts in the most generous sense — drafts that improve through pushback, drafts that exist to be built upon rather than received as final. If you find errors, missing events, chains that should be drawn differently, regional histories that deserve more depth than I have given them, please write. The work belongs to anyone who wants to use it for thinking clearly about where we are.

